'''Pauline Neura Reilly''' [[Order of Australia|OAM]] (5 December 1918 – 22 April 2011) was an Australian author and [[ornithologist]].

==Early years==
Reilly was born (as Pauline Duncan) in [[Adelaide]].  Her family moved to [[Melbourne]] where she attended [[Korowa Anglican Girls' School]] and [[Melbourne Girls Grammar School]] until 1934. Before the [[Second World War]] she worked as a secretary, then served from 1942 to 1944 as a gunner in the [[Women's Auxiliary Australian Air Force]], as well as working for [[Australian Army Intelligence Corps|Australian Army Intelligence]].  She married Arthur Reilly in 1943.

==Ornithology==
Reilly joined the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] (RAOU) in 1956, which she served as Publicity Officer 1966–1967, on the Field Investigations Committee 1969–1972, as President 1972–1975, and as the Chair of the Atlas Committee 1976–1982.  From 1969 to 1970 she was President of the [[Australian Bird Study Association|Bird Banders' Association of Australia]].  From 1964 to 1981 she was the Honorary Regional Victorian Organiser of the [[Australian Bird and Bat Banding Scheme]].  One of her main achievements with the RAOU was the instigation, leadership and successful conclusion of the RAOU's first [[Atlas of Australian Birds]] project, fieldwork for which ran from 1 January 1977 to 31 December 1981.

Reilly was actively involved in ornithological fieldwork for many years, especially in studies of [[little penguin]]s. In 1968 she founded the Penguin Study Group of the [[Victorian Ornithological Research Group]].  In 1973 she led an expedition to the [[Great Australian Bight]] to carry out penguin research.  In 1978–79 she became the first woman to spend the summer research season on subantarctic [[Macquarie Island]] to [[bird ringing|band]] penguins.  She was invited to open the Second International Penguin Conference in August 1992.

In later years Reilly moved to [[Aireys Inlet, Victoria|Aireys Inlet]] on the Victorian coast where she concentrated on writing a series of scientifically accurate [[children's literature|children's books]] about Australian birds and other animals, mainly illustrated first by Will Rolland and later by Kaylene Traynor.

==Honours==
* 1981 – elected a [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union Fellows|Fellow of the RAOU]]
* 1987 and 1992 – received [[Whitley Awards (Australia)|Whitley Book Award]]s for Best Children's Series from the [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales]]
* 1994 – awarded the Medal of the [[Order of Australia]] (OAM) for service to ornithology
* 1994 – awarded the [[The Wilderness Society (Australia)|Wilderness Society]] Award for Children's Literature (non-fiction)
* 2001 – awarded the RAOU's [[John Hobbs Medal]] for contributions to amateur ornithology in Australia
* 2005 – awarded the [[W. Roy Wheeler Medallion]] for contributions to field ornithology by [[Bird Observation & Conservation Australia]]

