{{for|the 1918 poem by American poet Joyce Kilmer|Rouge Bouquet (poem)}} [[File:Rouge Bouquet Fighting 69th Memorial Service World War I March 1918.gif|thumb|right|300px|Memorial service held by soldiers of the "Fighting 69th" for 19 men lost in the 7 March 1918 Rouge Bouquet bombardment]] '''Rouge Bouquet''' is a part of the [[Parroy|Forêt de Parroy]] near the [[France|French]] village of [[Baccarat, Meurthe-et-Moselle|Baccarat]] that was the site of a German artillery bombardment of American trench positions on 7 March 1918 at 15:20 on the [[Chausailles sector]] of the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] during [[World War I]].<ref>National Archives and Records Administration - Washington, DC. ''CR Rouge Bouquet held by 2nd Btn 165th A.I.R. 7–8 March 1918, NA/RG 120: World War I Organizational Records: 42nd Division, Box 27, Folder—Rept. Of Events in CR Rouge Bouquet''</ref><ref name="FatherDuffysStory">Duffy, Francis Patrick. Father Duffy’s Story. (New York: George H. Doran Company, 1919), 350.</ref> The bombardment resulted in the burial of 21 men of the [[165th Infantry Regiment]], [[42nd Infantry Division (United States)|42nd Rainbow Division]] (originally the [[69th Infantry Regiment (New York)|69th Regiment]] of the [[New York National Guard]]) of which only a few survived. The 22 men, including their platoon commander 1st Lieutenant John Norman, were assembled in a dugout when a German artillery shell landed on the roof of the dugout. A rescue effort by Major [[Wild Bill Donovan|William J. "Wild Bill" Donovan]] was begun in haste attempting to dig the men but their efforts were hampered by mud-slides and continued enemy shelling.<ref name="FatherDuffysStory"/><ref name="HarrisDuffysWar">Harris, Stephen L. Duffy's War: Fr. Francis Duffy, Wild Bill Donovan, and the Irish Fighting 69th in World War I (Washington, DC: Potomac Books Inc, 2007).</ref>{{rp|pp.167–171}} Two men were rescued and five dead were recovered before efforts had to be halted. The voices of other men could be heard for a while, but the remaining fifteen men died before rescue efforts could resume.<ref name="HarrisDuffysWar"/>{{rp|pp.167–171}} Donovan was awarded the French [[Croix de Guerre]] for his actions during the attempted rescue.<ref name="HarrisDuffysWar"/>{{rp|pp.209–210}}
Poet and literary critic [[Joyce Kilmer]], a sergeant with the regiment, wrote the 1918 poem "[[Rouge Bouquet (poem)|Rouge Bouquet]]" (also called "The Wood Called Rouge Bouquet" to commemorate the soldiers in his unit who died.<ref name="HarrisDuffysWar"/>{{rp|pp.175–176}} The poem was first read by Kilmer at the memorial service held on the battlefield a few days later.<ref name="HarrisDuffysWar"/>{{rp|pp.175–176}} It first appeared in print in the American serviceman's newspaper ''Stars and Stripes''—published two weeks after Kilmer died in combat in the [[Second Battle of the Marne]] on 30 July 1918.<ref>Kilmer, Joyce. "Rouge Bouquet" in ''Stars and Stripes'' (16 August 1918).</ref><ref>Mitgang, Herbert. ''Civilians Under Arms: The Stars and Stripes, Civil War to Korea''. (SIU Press, 1959), 146-148.</ref><ref>United States Army. Army Expeditionary Force, 1917-1919. (New York: G.P. Putnam's sons, 1919), 78-80.</ref>
